<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="439" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,383]" pageId="4" pageNumber="439">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,256,279]" pageId="4" pageNumber="439">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. This new species is related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Furukawa" authorityName="Furukawa" authorityYear="1970" box="[654,909,255,279]" class="Insecta" family="Trigonidiidae" genus="Usgmona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="439" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="genji" subGenus="Usgmona">
<emphasis box="[654,678,255,278]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="439">A.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[695,721,256,279]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="439">U.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[738,791,256,279]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="439">genji</emphasis>
Furukawa
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished by the epiphallus very long, with posterior margin distinctly emarginated in middle; endophallus bifurcated at base and pointed at apex. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,320,325,348]" pageId="4" pageNumber="439">Etymology</emphasis>
. The new specific name is derived from Latin ex- (out) + cavare (cave), referring to posterior margin of epiphallus distinctly emarginated in middle.
</paragraph>
